# =============================================================================
# CONVERSION PROMPT: .bashrc -> .bashrc.example
# =============================================================================
# 
# This file is a generic template converted from personal .bashrc.
# When updating from .bashrc, follow these principles to maintain a generic version:
#
# REMOVAL PRINCIPLES - Remove anything that is:
#   1. Personal/Private Information:
#      - Hardcoded personal paths (e.g., $HOME/custom/path, specific repo paths)
#      - Personal usernames, hostnames, or identifiers
#      - Personal commit messages, prompts, or symbols
#   2. External Dependencies:
#      - Functions/variables that download from specific URLs (GitHub, etc.)
#      - Functions that depend on external scripts not in the repo
#      - Auto-download or auto-update mechanisms
#   3. Environment-Specific:
#      - Proxy configurations (unless truly universal)
#      - Personal service configurations
#      - Machine-specific paths or settings
#   4. Personal Workflows:
#      - Wrapper functions for personal tools/workflows
#      - Personal shortcuts to specific projects/locations
#      - Custom integrations with personal services
#   5. Dependent Items:
#      - Aliases that call removed functions
#      - Variables only used by removed functions
#      - Conditional blocks that depend on personal paths
#
# KEEP PRINCIPLES - Keep anything that is:
#   1. Universal Shell Configuration:
#      - Standard bash options (shopt, history, completion)
#      - Terminal behavior settings
#      - Generic prompt configurations (with neutral symbols)
#   2. Generic Utilities:
#      - Functions that work with standard tools (ls, grep, find, etc.)
#      - Path manipulation utilities (if path-agnostic)
#      - Generic file/directory operations
#      - Standard tool wrappers (if they don't hardcode paths)
#   3. Cross-Platform Support:
#      - OS detection and conditional paths (Linux/Darwin)
#      - Standard PATH additions (HOME/.bin, .local/bin, etc.)
#      - Universal tool configurations (FZF, etc.)
#   4. Reusable Patterns:
#      - Generic aliases for common commands
#      - Color/formatting variables
#      - Helper functions that don't depend on personal setup
#
# CONVERSION PROCESS:
#   1. Review each function/alias/variable:
#      - Does it reference personal paths? → Remove or generalize
#      - Does it download from external sources? → Remove
#      - Does it depend on personal tools/services? → Remove
#      - Is it truly generic and reusable? → Keep
#   2. Check dependencies:
#      - If a function is removed, remove aliases that call it
#      - If a variable is removed, remove functions that use it
#   3. Generalize remaining items:
#      - Replace personal paths with generic patterns
#      - Replace personal symbols with neutral ones
#      - Ensure no hardcoded personal information
#   4. Verify:
#      - No personal identifiers remain
#      - No external download dependencies
#      - File loads without errors
#      - All kept functions are truly generic
#
# =============================================================================

# Disable the default interactive shell warning
export BASH_SILENCE_DEPRECATION_WARNING=1

# ~/.bashrc file for bash interactive shells

# If not running interactively, don't do anything
